╔══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╗
║  HELIX TRAINER — Exercise 6.3: Duplicate Cursors                ║
║  Category: Multi-Selection         Difficulty: ★★☆ Intermediate  ║
╚══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝

COMMANDS TO LEARN
─────────────────
  C       Copy selection to the next line (add cursor below)
  Alt-C   Copy selection to the previous line (add cursor above)

These create column-style editing — perfect for adding the same
text to multiple consecutive lines.

INSTRUCTIONS
────────────
  The list below needs "- [ ] " (a markdown checkbox) added to
  the beginning of every line.

  Strategy:
  1. Move to the beginning of the first line ("Clean up")
     Press  gh  to go to line start (or Home key)
  2. Now press  C  four times — this copies your cursor down to
     each subsequent line. You should see 5 cursors total, one
     at the start of each line.
  3. Press  i  to enter insert mode (at all 5 cursors)
  4. Type   - [ ]   (dash, space, open bracket, space, close
     bracket, space)
  5. Press  Esc

  All five lines now have checkboxes. This is column editing,
  Helix style.

────────────────────────── PRACTICE ──────────────────────────────

Clean up the kitchen
Fix the leaky faucet
Organize the garage
Update the budget spreadsheet
Call the dentist for an appointment

────────────────────────── EXPECTED ──────────────────────────────

- [ ] Clean up the kitchen
- [ ] Fix the leaky faucet
- [ ] Organize the garage
- [ ] Update the budget spreadsheet
- [ ] Call the dentist for an appointment

──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
HINTS (read only if stuck):
  Hint 1: Make sure your cursor is at column 1 of the first line
          before you start pressing C. Use gh or Home.
  Hint 2: Press C exactly 4 times (not 5) — you already have
          one cursor on the first line, so 4 copies gives you 5.
  Hint 3: If your cursors are misaligned, undo with u and try
          again. All lines must start at the same column for
          C to work cleanly.
  Hint 4: Alt-C works the same but upward — useful when you're
          at the bottom of a block and want to add cursors above.
